Notes:
- The data quality check revealed all unique values for the serial_number column.
- I started my approach to this problem by extracting the month number from the activity date column using
  the mutate() and month() functions. Next, I counted the number of inspections per month across all years
  using the group_by(), summarise(), and n() functions. After aggregation, I filtered for the month with
  the lowest number of inspections using the slice_min() function. From there, I converted the month number
  to month in text form using the mutate() and month() functions. Lastly, I selected the relevant output 
  columns using the select() function.

Suggestions and Final Thoughts:
- R treats the month string as a factor where a label is attached to a stored integer. Grouping by a factor
  is as fast as grouping by an integer itself because R is essentially groupng the underlying integer codes.
  In other languages, it is best to group by an integer then convert the integer later to text. The number
  first approach is important for datasets that are massive, when joining tables, and other custom logic.
  ex.
      mutate(
          month = month(activity_date, label=TRUE, abbr=FALSE)
      )
- To be more concise and "tidy", the month name can be extracted from the activity_date column and be used
  to count the number of inspections per month by utilizing the count() function. The count() function is
  shorthand for group_by(), summarise(), and n(). This is seen in Solution #2.
  ex.
      count(
          month, name="num_inspections"
      ) 
- One of my other approaches was to use the floor_date() function from the lubridate package for extracting
  the month from the activity_date column. However, the prompt specifies to find the lowest number of
  inspections for each month across all years as opposed to each month and year. Since the year was not
  necessary, the month() function became the better option.

